President Xi Jinping of China visited the United States for a State visit in September 2015. During the visit, President Obama and President Xi discussed a range of global, regional, and bilateral issues. They agreed to work together in various areas, including addressing global and regional challenges such as supporting reconstruction and economic development in Afghanistan, peacekeeping efforts, nuclear security, wildlife trafficking, and ocean conservation. They also focused on strengthening development cooperation, particularly in the areas of food security, public health, and humanitarian assistance. In terms of bilateral relations, they discussed military relations, cybersecurity, law enforcement, and counterterrorism. Additionally, they announced two new initiatives to enhance people-to-people exchange between the two countries, including a U.S.-China Tourism Year and the "One Million Strong" initiative to have one million American students studying Mandarin by 2020.